[normal]Written evidence from Scope (PEX 0022)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]1.1 
[normal]Scope exists to make this country a better place for disabled people and their families. We do this by running a range of services, raising awareness of the issues 
[normal]that disabled people face and influencing change across society.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We provide support, advice and information for more than a quarter of a million disabled people and their family members every year.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2 Scope welcomes the opportunity 
[normal]to submit written evid
[normal]ence to the 
[normal]Committee’s Inquiry and would be happy to provide oral evidence if requested.
[normal] Our submission focuses on the questions relating to 
[normal]public expenditure on 
[normal]social care.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.1 Social care is the support that enables disabled people to liv
[normal]e independently and with dignity. It supports
[normal] 
[normal]them to 
[normal]do essential day to day tasks such as washing, dress
[normal]ing, eating as well as living independent lives in their community.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2 Working aged disabled people make up one third of social care users - i
[normal]n 2012
[normal]/13
[normal], there were 
[normal]434
[normal],
[normal]775
[normal] working-aged disabled people in the social care system - out of a total of 1,332,995
[normal]. However, demographic changes mean the numbers of working-aged disabled people needing care are projected to rise by 9.2%
[normal] from 2010 to 2020. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3. [bold]The impact on the provision of adult social care of the 2010 spending review settlement and the ability of local authorities to make the necessary efficiency savings[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1 
[normal]Scope welcome
[normal]d
[normal] the Government’s commitment to investing 
[normal]an extra 
[normal]£1bn in social ca
[normal]re in the 2010 Spending Review
[normal] which was an important recognition of the increasing pressures on the social care system.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2 However as funding for social care is not ring-fenced, th
[normal]is investment must be seen in the context 
[normal]of a 33% cut in local 
[normal]councils’ budgets by 2014/15
[normal] and the chronic long term 
[normal]underfunding of the social care system
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3. 
[normal]O
[normal]ver the past three years, £2.68 billion has been cut from adult social care - 20 per cent of net spending
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal] With
[normal] the increasing numbers of disabled adults who need care and support
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]we are concerned that the Government’s investment will not ensure the sustainable funding of the social care system
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]4
[normal] 
[normal]As a result of these 
[normal]pressures
[normal], alongside an ageing population, 
[normal]many local authorities have been raising the threshold at which disabled people become eligible for support. 
[normal]However this trend began even before 2010. 
[normal]In 2005, 50% of local authorities set their eligibility criteria at ‘
[normal]Moderate’ needs but
[normal] 
[normal]b
[normal]y 2012, 84% ha
[normal]d set their eligibility criteria at
[normal] the 
[normal]higher ‘substantial’ needs
[normal], meaning t
[normal]hat s
[normal]ince 200
[normal]7/
[normal]8 the number of people using care has 
[normal]gradually 
[normal]fallen by at least 
[normal]347
[normal],000
[normal] (see table below)
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]As a result, just 14% of those with ‘moderate’ FACS needs are 
[normal]receiving care
[normal], while 
[normal]at least
[normal] 800,000 people with care needs are not receiving any support at all
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
