[normal]3.5 
[normal]Unless a sustainable source of funding for adult social care is found, this situation is only likely to get worse. The 
[normal]LGA has
[normal] estimated that spending on social care will 
[normal]sur
[normal]pass 45% of council budgets by 
[normal]2019/20
[normal], meaning that councils will have to cut social care further or drastically reduce budgets for other services
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]6
[normal] Research
[normal] by Scope and four oth
[normal]er leading disability charities in “
[normal]The Other Care Crisis
[normal]”
[normal] report 
[normal]has found that 
[normal]this chronic underf
[normal]unding of social care has had a significant impact on disabled people’s lives:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]7
[normal] But recent e
[normal]conomic modelling by Deloitte, contained in the 
[normal]Ending the Care Crisis
[normal] report, has shown that
[normal] investment in social care can lead to significant financial savings for 
[normal]the NHS, central 
[normal]Government and Local Authorities
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]For example, a £1.2 billion investment in care for people with ‘moderate’ level needs would result in:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A
[normal] £570 million saving to the NHS and local government
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A
[normal] £700 million saving to Central Government:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.8 
[normal]As evidenced above, there are
[normal] clear 
[normal]long term 
[normal]economic benefits to local authorities, the NHS and the Treasury of 
[normal]investing in care for people with lower level needs
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]W
[normal]e 
[normal]therefore 
[normal]recommend the Government sets the new ‘national eligibility threshold’, as set out in the regulations accompanying the Care Bill, at a level 
[normal]equivalent
[normal] to
[normal] 
[normal]‘Moderate’ 
[normal]under the current 
[normal]FACs
[normal] s
[normal]ystem
[normal].
[normal]4. [bold]The impact on NHS plans of decisions currently being made by local authorities and the use of the additional funding for social care being made available through the NHS budget[bold]4.1 
[normal]We 
[normal]wholly
[normal] welcome the 
[normal]creation of a £3
[normal].8bn 
[normal]Integration Transforma
[normal]tion Fund (including a £2bn transfer from the NHS budget) to ensure better integration between health and social care announced 
[normal]in the Spending Review in June this 
[normal]year
[normal], 
[normal]particularly 
[normal]that 
[normal]it will be spent through Health and Wellbeing Boards. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2 
[normal]We also 
[normal]welcome the conditions that are attached to the funding which will ensure a joint approach to assessments and care planning will be taken, as well as there being a professional who will be accountable where funding is used for integrated packages of care.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3 However, given the extent of the long-term underinvestment in social care, we have strong concerns that this transfer of funding will be inadequate to meet the growing needs of working-aged disabled people and additional investment is needed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4 Mor
[normal]eover, t
[normal]he Integration Transformation Fund is predominantly to support people being discharged from hospital- the majority of whom are likely to older people and therefore the vast majority of younger working age d
[normal]isabled people may not benefit. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5 By f
[normal]ocussing on delayed transfers of care, emergency admissions and readmissions into hospital, and out of hours/weekend packages
[normal], it is also 
[normal]likely 
[normal]that the ITF will 
[normal]reduce existing 
[normal]problems rather than unmet need. Therefore it i
[normal]s likely that investment in mo
[normal]re 
[normal]preventative, 
[normal]community- based 
[normal]s
[normal]ervices will 
[normal]continue to
[normal] be neglected.
